{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_762db21e06ce46ab9fa59c2d","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Requirements: Simple Kanban Practice App\n2\t\n3\t**Defined:** 2026-05-08\n4\t**Core Value:** Working end-to-end Kanban board — add, move, and delete tasks across three columns in a browser.\n5\t\n6\t## v1 Requirements\n7\t\n8\t### Database\n9\t\n10\t- [ ] **DB-01**: Create `tasks` table with id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, title VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL, status VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'todo', created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW()\n11\t- [ ] **DB-02**: Seed database with sample tasks across all three statuses for testing\n12\t\n13\t### API\n14\t\n15\t- [ ] **API-01**: GET /tasks returns all tasks as JSON array\n16\t- [ ] **API-02**: POST /tasks creates task with title (expects {\"title\": \"string\"}), defaults status to 'todo'\n17\t- [ ] **API-03**: PUT /tasks/:id updates task status (expects {\"status\": \"string\"})\n18\t- [ ] **API-04**: DELETE /tasks/:id deletes task\n19\t\n20\t### Frontend\n21\t\n22\t- [ ] **FE-01**: Fetch all tasks on page load and render in three columns: \"To Do\", \"In Progress\", \"Done\"\n23\t- [ ] **FE-02**: Text input + \"Add Task\" button at top of page creates new task\n24\t- [ ] **FE-03**: Each task card shows title, status dropdown, and delete button\n25\t- [ ] **FE-04**: Changing status dropdown moves task to correct column\n26\t- [ ] **FE-05**: Delete button removes task from board\n27\t- [ ] **FE-06**: After any add/update/delete, refetch and re-render all tasks\n28\t\n29\t### Infrastructure\n30\t\n31\t- [ ] **INF-01**: Express server serves static index.html on startup\n32\t- [ ] **INF-02**: PostgreSQL connection configured with hardcoded credentials\n33\t- [ ] **INF-03**: package.json with express and pg dependencies\n34\t\n35\t## v2 Requirements\n36\t\n37\t(None — this is a practice app, no planned extensions)\n38\t\n39\t## Out of Scope\n40\t\n41\t| Feature | Reason |\n42\t|---------|--------|\n43\t| Authentication | Local practice only, not production |\n44\t| Input validation | Spec explicitly excludes |\n45\t| Error handling | Spec explicitly excludes |\n46\t| Logging | Spec explicitly excludes |\n47\t| Pagination | Small dataset expected |\n48\t| Environment variables | Hardcoded credentials acceptable for practice |\n49\t| Docker | Local PostgreSQL only |\n50\t| Testing | Practice project, not production |\n51\t| CI/CD | No pipeline needed |\n52\t| CORS config | Allow all origins |\n53\t| Drag-and-drop | Dropdown-based status change only |\n54\t| Animations | Spec explicitly excludes |\n55\t| CSS frameworks | Inline CSS only |\n56\t\n57\t## Traceability\n58\t\n59\t| Requirement | Phase | Status |\n60\t|-------------|-------|--------|\n61\t| DB-01 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n62\t| DB-02 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n63\t| API-01 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n64\t| API-02 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n65\t| API-03 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n66\t| API-04 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n67\t| FE-01 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n68\t| FE-02 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n69\t| FE-03 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n70\t| FE-04 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n71\t| FE-05 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n72\t| FE-06 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n73\t| INF-01 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n74\t| INF-02 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n75\t| INF-03 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n76\t\n77\t**Coverage:**\n78\t- v1 requirements: 15 total\n79\t- Mapped to phases: 15\n80\t- Unmapped: 0\n81\t\n82\t---\n83\t*Requirements defined: 2026-05-08*\n84\t*Last updated: 2026-05-08 after initial definition*\n85\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bae0887d-b1fa-41c2-a958-e7e199ec0d46","uuid":"253fa511-ca0b-45eb-94c0-884752b3912f","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:01:19.082Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"F:/simpleKanbanapp/.planning/REQUIREMENTS.md","content":"# Requirements: Simple Kanban Practice App\n\n**Defined:** 2026-05-08\n**Core Value:** Working end-to-end Kanban board — add, move, and delete tasks across three columns in a browser.\n\n## v1 Requirements\n\n### Database\n\n- [ ] **DB-01**: Create `tasks` table with id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, title VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL, status VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'todo', created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW()\n- [ ] **DB-02**: Seed database with sample tasks across all three statuses for testing\n\n### API\n\n- [ ] **API-01**: GET /tasks returns all tasks as JSON array\n- [ ] **API-02**: POST /tasks creates task with title (expects {\"title\": \"string\"}), defaults status to 'todo'\n- [ ] **API-03**: PUT /tasks/:id updates task status (expects {\"status\": \"string\"})\n- [ ] **API-04**: DELETE /tasks/:id deletes task\n\n### Frontend\n\n- [ ] **FE-01**: Fetch all tasks on page load and render in three columns: \"To Do\", \"In Progress\", \"Done\"\n- [ ] **FE-02**: Text input + \"Add Task\" button at top of page creates new task\n- [ ] **FE-03**: Each task card shows title, status dropdown, and delete button\n- [ ] **FE-04**: Changing status dropdown moves task to correct column\n- [ ] **FE-05**: Delete button removes task from board\n- [ ] **FE-06**: After any add/update/delete, refetch and re-render all tasks\n\n### Infrastructure\n\n- [ ] **INF-01**: Express server serves static index.html on startup\n- [ ] **INF-02**: PostgreSQL connection configured with hardcoded credentials\n- [ ] **INF-03**: package.json with express and pg dependencies\n\n## v2 Requirements\n\n(None — this is a practice app, no planned extensions)\n\n## Out of Scope\n\n| Feature | Reason |\n|---------|--------|\n| Authentication | Local practice only, not production |\n| Input validation | Spec explicitly excludes |\n| Error handling | Spec explicitly excludes |\n| Logging | Spec explicitly excludes |\n| Pagination | Small dataset expected |\n| Environment variables | Hardcoded credentials acceptable for practice |\n| Docker | Local PostgreSQL only |\n| Testing | Practice project, not production |\n| CI/CD | No pipeline needed |\n| CORS config | Allow all origins |\n| Drag-and-drop | Dropdown-based status change only |\n| Animations | Spec explicitly excludes |\n| CSS frameworks | Inline CSS only |\n\n## Traceability\n\n| Requirement | Phase | Status |\n|-------------|-------|--------|\n| DB-01 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| DB-02 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| API-01 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| API-02 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| API-03 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| API-04 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| FE-01 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| FE-02 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| FE-03 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| FE-04 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| FE-05 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| FE-06 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| INF-01 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| INF-02 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n| INF-03 | Phase 1 | Pending |\n\n**Coverage:**\n- v1 requirements: 15 total\n- Mapped to phases: 15\n- Unmapped: 0\n\n---\n*Requirements defined: 2026-05-08*\n*Last updated: 2026-05-08 after initial definition*\n","numLines":85,"startLine":1,"totalLines":85}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_064503ccf9884d96a1c9e767","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Design: Simple Kanban Practice App\n2\t\n3\tGenerated by /office-hours on 2026-05-07\n4\tBranch: unknown\n5\tRepo: F:\\simpleKanbanapp (greenfield)\n6\tStatus: APPROVED\n7\tMode: Builder\n8\tSupersedes: Hp-unknown-design-20260505-202841.md (FlowBoard — production Kanban)\n9\t\n10\t## Problem Statement\n11\t\n12\tBuild a minimal Kanban board for local practice. The goal is learning HTTP verbs, SQL queries, and frontend-backend communication through the simplest possible working app. No frameworks, no build tools, no abstractions — just Express, pg, and vanilla HTML.\n13\t\n14\tThe prior design (FlowBoard) was a full production Kanban with 10+ models, real-time collaboration, auth, drag-and-drop, and Next.js. This is the opposite: one table, four endpoints, three files. The learning happens in the plumbing, not the features.\n15\t\n16\t## What Makes This Cool\n17\t\n18\tThe simplicity IS the feature. You type `node server.js`, open `index.html`, and you have a working Kanban board. Every line of code maps to a concept: HTTP verbs, SQL queries, JSON serialization, DOM manipulation, fetch API. No magic. No \"it just works.\" You see exactly how a web app fits together.\n19\t\n20\tThe \"whoa\" moment: adding a task, watching it appear in the \"To Do\" column, dragging the dropdown to \"Done,\" and knowing exactly which HTTP request, SQL query, and DOM update made it happen.\n21\t\n22\t## Constraints\n23\t\n24\t- **Stack locked:** Node.js + Express + `pg` library, single `index.html` with inline CSS + vanilla JS\n25\t- **Single PostgreSQL table:** `tasks` with 4 columns\n26\t- **Four API endpoints max:** GET /tasks, POST /tasks, PUT /tasks/:id, DELETE /tasks/:id\n27\t- **Hardcoded DB credentials:** `host=localhost`, `port=5432`, `user=postgres`, `password=postgres`, `database=kanban_practice`\n28\t- **Zero production features:** No auth, no validation, no error handling, no logging, no pagination, no CORS configuration (allow all origins)\n29\t- **No external dependencies** beyond `express` and `pg`\n30\t- **No drag-and-drop, no animations, no frameworks, no build tools**\n31\t\n32\t## Premises\n33\t\n34\t1. **Single-table CRUD teaches fundamentals.** HTTP verbs map directly to SQL operations. No ORM, no abstraction layer. You write the query, you see the result.\n35\t2. **PostgreSQL is correct despite setup cost.** Learning real SQL against a real database is more valuable than SQLite's zero-config convenience. The `pg` library exposes connection pooling and query patterns that transfer to production.\n36\t3. **Vanilla HTML/CSS/JS is the right frontend.** Forces understanding of `fetch()`, DOM manipulation (`createElement`, `innerHTML`), and event listeners. No React, no virtual DOM, no state management — just the browser APIs.\n37\t4. **Refetch-after-mutation is fine.** Every add/update/delete triggers a fresh `GET /tasks`. No optimistic updates, no client-side state cache. The round-trip IS the lesson.\n38\t5. **Hardcoded credentials + zero error handling is acceptable.** This is a throwaway practice app that runs on localhost. Production patterns would obscure the fundamentals being learned.\n39\t\n40\t## Approaches Considered\n41\t\n42\t### Approach A: Node.js + Express + pg (chosen)\n43\tThree files. Bare-metal HTTP. You see every request, response, status code, and SQL query.\n44\t- Effort: S\n45\t- Risk: Low\n46\t\n47\t### Approach B: Python + FastAPI + psycopg2\n48\tAuto-generated Swagger docs, type hints, cleaner async patterns. But FastAPI's abstractions hide the HTTP plumbing being learned.\n49\t- Effort: S\n50\t- Risk: Low\n51\t\n52\t### Approach C: Express with minimal structure (4 files)\n53\tSplit server.js into routes + db connection + migration script. Teaches separation of concerns. Slightly more files but same concepts.\n54\t\n55\t## Recommended Approach\n56\t\n57\t**Approach A: Node.js + Express + pg.** Three files. The most direct path to learning HTTP fundamentals. Express shows you exactly what happens with each request — no decorators, no dependency injection, no magic. You write `app.get('/tasks', ...)`, you see the SQL query, you return the JSON. That's it.\n58\t\n59\t## File Structure\n60\t\n61\t```\n62\tF:\\simpleKanbanapp\\\n63\t├── server.js        # Express server: pg connection + 4 CRUD endpoints\n64\t├── index.html       # Single HTML file: inline CSS + vanilla JS + 3-column layout\n65\t└── package.json     # { dependencies: { \"express\": \"^4.x\", \"pg\": \"^8.x\" } }\n66\t```\n67\t\n68\tTotal: 3 files. ~150 lines of code across all three.\n69\t\n70\t## Database\n71\t\n72\t### Connection\n73\t- Host: `localhost`\n74\t- Port: `5432`\n75\t- User: `postgres`\n76\t- Password: `postgres`\n77\t- Database: `kanban_practice`\n78\t\n79\t### Schema\n80\t```sql\n81\tCREATE TABLE tasks (\n82\t  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n83\t  title VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,\n84\t  status VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'todo',\n85\t  created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW()\n86\t);\n87\t```\n88\t\n89\t### Allowed statuses\n90\t- `'todo'`\n91\t- `'in_progress'`\n92\t- `'done'`\n93\t\n94\t## API Endpoints\n95\t\n96\t| Method | Path | Request Body | Response | Description |\n97\t|--------|------|-------------|----------|-------------|\n98\t| GET | `/tasks` | — | `{ tasks: [...] }` | Returns all tasks |\n99\t| POST | `/tasks` | `{ \"title\": \"string\" }` | `{ task: {...} }` | Creates a task (status defaults to `'todo'`) |\n100\t| PUT | `/tasks/:id` | `{ \"status\": \"string\" }` | `{ task: {...} }` | Updates task status |\n101\t| DELETE | `/tasks/:id` | — | `{ success: true }` | Deletes a task |\n102\t\n103\tAll endpoints return JSON. `server.js` serves `index.html` via `express.static(__dirname)` so the frontend is served at `GET /` on the same origin as the API. No CORS configuration needed.\n104\t\n105\t## Frontend\n106\t\n107\t### Layout\n108\t- **Top:** Text input + \"Add Task\" button\n109\t- **Below:** Three columns side by side: \"To Do\" | \"In Progress\" | \"Done\"\n110\t\n111\t### Task Card\n112\tEach card shows:\n113\t- Task title\n114\t- `<select>` dropdown with three options: `todo`, `in_progress`, `done`\n115\t- \"Delete\" button\n116\t\n117\t### Behavior\n118\t1. On page load: `fetch('/tasks')` → render cards into correct columns\n119\t2. \"Add Task\" click: `fetch('/tasks', { method: 'POST', body: ... })` → refetch all → re-render\n120\t3. Dropdown change: `fetch('/tasks/:id', { method: 'PUT', body: ... })` → refetch all → re-render\n121\t4. \"Delete\" click: `fetch('/tasks/:id', { method: 'DELETE' })` → refetch all → re-render\n122\t\n123\t### Styling\n124\tBasic inline CSS only. Three-column layout (flexbox or grid). Minimal card styling. No color palette, no design system.\n125\t\n126\t## Setup Commands\n127\t\n128\t```bash\n129\t# (a) Create database and table\n130\tcreatedb kanban_practice\n131\tpsql -d kanban_practice -c \"CREATE TABLE tasks (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, title VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL, status VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'todo', created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW());\"\n132\t\n133\t# (b) Install dependencies\n134\tnpm init -y\n135\tnpm install express pg\n136\t\n137\t# (c) Start the app\n138\tnode server.js\n139\t```\n140\t\n141\tThen open `http://localhost:3000` in a browser. Express serves `index.html` as a static file.\n142\t\n143\t## Open Questions\n144\t\n145\tNone. The spec is fully determined.\n146\t\n147\t## Success Criteria\n148\t\n149\t- [ ] `createdb kanban_practice` succeeds\n150\t- [ ] `CREATE TABLE tasks` succeeds\n151\t- [ ] `node server.js` starts without errors\n152\t- [ ] `GET /tasks` returns an empty array initially\n153\t- [ ] `POST /tasks` with `{ \"title\": \"Test\" }` creates a task with status `'todo'`\n154\t- [ ] `PUT /tasks/1` with `{ \"status\": \"done\" }` updates the task status\n155\t- [ ] `DELETE /tasks/1` removes the task\n156\t- [ ] Frontend shows three columns: \"To Do\", \"In Progress\", \"Done\"\n157\t- [ ] Adding a task makes it appear in \"To Do\"\n158\t- [ ] Changing the dropdown moves the task to the correct column\n159\t- [ ] Deleting a task removes it from the view\n160\t- [ ] Page refresh preserves data (it's in PostgreSQL)\n161\t\n162\t## Distribution Plan\n163\t\n164\tLocal only. No distribution. Run with `node server.js`, open `index.html` in browser.\n165\t\n166\t## Next Steps\n167\t\n168\t1. Create the PostgreSQL database and `tasks` table\n169\t2. Initialize the Node.js project (`npm init -y && npm install express pg`)\n170\t3. Write `server.js` with the pg connection and 4 CRUD endpoints\n171\t4. Write `index.html` with the 3-column layout, task cards, and fetch-based CRUD\n172\t5. Test: add a task, move it through columns, delete it, refresh to verify persistence\n173\t\n174\t## The Assignment\n175\t\n176\tOpen `psql` and run the CREATE TABLE command yourself — type it out, don't copy-paste. You'll learn more from the typos and error messages than from getting it right the first time.\n177\t\n178\t## What I noticed about how you think\n179\t\n180\t- You had the FlowBoard spec two days ago — a full production Kanban with 10+ models, real-time sync, auth, drag-and-drop. Now you're here with one table and four endpoints. That's not giving up — that's knowing that learning fundamentals first makes the complex version actually buildable. That instinct separates people who build things from people who design things.\n181\t- Your \"strictly exclude\" list was longer than your feature list. No auth, no validation, no error handling, no Docker, no testing, no CORS config, no drag-and-drop, no animations, no comments. That takes discipline. Most people can't resist adding \"just one more thing.\" You can.\n182\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bae0887d-b1fa-41c2-a958-e7e199ec0d46","uuid":"9357aeee-794a-4384-aed6-11a51f7de972","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:01:19.243Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"F:/simpleKanbanapp/Docs/Spec.md","content":"# Design: Simple Kanban Practice App\n\nGenerated by /office-hours on 2026-05-07\nBranch: unknown\nRepo: F:\\simpleKanbanapp (greenfield)\nStatus: APPROVED\nMode: Builder\nSupersedes: Hp-unknown-design-20260505-202841.md (FlowBoard — production Kanban)\n\n## Problem Statement\n\nBuild a minimal Kanban board for local practice. The goal is learning HTTP verbs, SQL queries, and frontend-backend communication through the simplest possible working app. No frameworks, no build tools, no abstractions — just Express, pg, and vanilla HTML.\n\nThe prior design (FlowBoard) was a full production Kanban with 10+ models, real-time collaboration, auth, drag-and-drop, and Next.js. This is the opposite: one table, four endpoints, three files. The learning happens in the plumbing, not the features.\n\n## What Makes This Cool\n\nThe simplicity IS the feature. You type `node server.js`, open `index.html`, and you have a working Kanban board. Every line of code maps to a concept: HTTP verbs, SQL queries, JSON serialization, DOM manipulation, fetch API. No magic. No \"it just works.\" You see exactly how a web app fits together.\n\nThe \"whoa\" moment: adding a task, watching it appear in the \"To Do\" column, dragging the dropdown to \"Done,\" and knowing exactly which HTTP request, SQL query, and DOM update made it happen.\n\n## Constraints\n\n- **Stack locked:** Node.js + Express + `pg` library, single `index.html` with inline CSS + vanilla JS\n- **Single PostgreSQL table:** `tasks` with 4 columns\n- **Four API endpoints max:** GET /tasks, POST /tasks, PUT /tasks/:id, DELETE /tasks/:id\n- **Hardcoded DB credentials:** `host=localhost`, `port=5432`, `user=postgres`, `password=postgres`, `database=kanban_practice`\n- **Zero production features:** No auth, no validation, no error handling, no logging, no pagination, no CORS configuration (allow all origins)\n- **No external dependencies** beyond `express` and `pg`\n- **No drag-and-drop, no animations, no frameworks, no build tools**\n\n## Premises\n\n1. **Single-table CRUD teaches fundamentals.** HTTP verbs map directly to SQL operations. No ORM, no abstraction layer. You write the query, you see the result.\n2. **PostgreSQL is correct despite setup cost.** Learning real SQL against a real database is more valuable than SQLite's zero-config convenience. The `pg` library exposes connection pooling and query patterns that transfer to production.\n3. **Vanilla HTML/CSS/JS is the right frontend.** Forces understanding of `fetch()`, DOM manipulation (`createElement`, `innerHTML`), and event listeners. No React, no virtual DOM, no state management — just the browser APIs.\n4. **Refetch-after-mutation is fine.** Every add/update/delete triggers a fresh `GET /tasks`. No optimistic updates, no client-side state cache. The round-trip IS the lesson.\n5. **Hardcoded credentials + zero error handling is acceptable.** This is a throwaway practice app that runs on localhost. Production patterns would obscure the fundamentals being learned.\n\n## Approaches Considered\n\n### Approach A: Node.js + Express + pg (chosen)\nThree files. Bare-metal HTTP. You see every request, response, status code, and SQL query.\n- Effort: S\n- Risk: Low\n\n### Approach B: Python + FastAPI + psycopg2\nAuto-generated Swagger docs, type hints, cleaner async patterns. But FastAPI's abstractions hide the HTTP plumbing being learned.\n- Effort: S\n- Risk: Low\n\n### Approach C: Express with minimal structure (4 files)\nSplit server.js into routes + db connection + migration script. Teaches separation of concerns. Slightly more files but same concepts.\n\n## Recommended Approach\n\n**Approach A: Node.js + Express + pg.** Three files. The most direct path to learning HTTP fundamentals. Express shows you exactly what happens with each request — no decorators, no dependency injection, no magic. You write `app.get('/tasks', ...)`, you see the SQL query, you return the JSON. That's it.\n\n## File Structure\n\n```\nF:\\simpleKanbanapp\\\n├── server.js        # Express server: pg connection + 4 CRUD endpoints\n├── index.html       # Single HTML file: inline CSS + vanilla JS + 3-column layout\n└── package.json     # { dependencies: { \"express\": \"^4.x\", \"pg\": \"^8.x\" } }\n```\n\nTotal: 3 files. ~150 lines of code across all three.\n\n## Database\n\n### Connection\n- Host: `localhost`\n- Port: `5432`\n- User: `postgres`\n- Password: `postgres`\n- Database: `kanban_practice`\n\n### Schema\n```sql\nCREATE TABLE tasks (\n  id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY,\n  title VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL,\n  status VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'todo',\n  created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW()\n);\n```\n\n### Allowed statuses\n- `'todo'`\n- `'in_progress'`\n- `'done'`\n\n## API Endpoints\n\n| Method | Path | Request Body | Response | Description |\n|--------|------|-------------|----------|-------------|\n| GET | `/tasks` | — | `{ tasks: [...] }` | Returns all tasks |\n| POST | `/tasks` | `{ \"title\": \"string\" }` | `{ task: {...} }` | Creates a task (status defaults to `'todo'`) |\n| PUT | `/tasks/:id` | `{ \"status\": \"string\" }` | `{ task: {...} }` | Updates task status |\n| DELETE | `/tasks/:id` | — | `{ success: true }` | Deletes a task |\n\nAll endpoints return JSON. `server.js` serves `index.html` via `express.static(__dirname)` so the frontend is served at `GET /` on the same origin as the API. No CORS configuration needed.\n\n## Frontend\n\n### Layout\n- **Top:** Text input + \"Add Task\" button\n- **Below:** Three columns side by side: \"To Do\" | \"In Progress\" | \"Done\"\n\n### Task Card\nEach card shows:\n- Task title\n- `<select>` dropdown with three options: `todo`, `in_progress`, `done`\n- \"Delete\" button\n\n### Behavior\n1. On page load: `fetch('/tasks')` → render cards into correct columns\n2. \"Add Task\" click: `fetch('/tasks', { method: 'POST', body: ... })` → refetch all → re-render\n3. Dropdown change: `fetch('/tasks/:id', { method: 'PUT', body: ... })` → refetch all → re-render\n4. \"Delete\" click: `fetch('/tasks/:id', { method: 'DELETE' })` → refetch all → re-render\n\n### Styling\nBasic inline CSS only. Three-column layout (flexbox or grid). Minimal card styling. No color palette, no design system.\n\n## Setup Commands\n\n```bash\n# (a) Create database and table\ncreatedb kanban_practice\npsql -d kanban_practice -c \"CREATE TABLE tasks (id SERIAL PRIMARY KEY, title VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL, status VARCHAR(20) DEFAULT 'todo', created_at TIMESTAMP DEFAULT NOW());\"\n\n# (b) Install dependencies\nnpm init -y\nnpm install express pg\n\n# (c) Start the app\nnode server.js\n```\n\nThen open `http://localhost:3000` in a browser. Express serves `index.html` as a static file.\n\n## Open Questions\n\nNone. The spec is fully determined.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\n- [ ] `createdb kanban_practice` succeeds\n- [ ] `CREATE TABLE tasks` succeeds\n- [ ] `node server.js` starts without errors\n- [ ] `GET /tasks` returns an empty array initially\n- [ ] `POST /tasks` with `{ \"title\": \"Test\" }` creates a task with status `'todo'`\n- [ ] `PUT /tasks/1` with `{ \"status\": \"done\" }` updates the task status\n- [ ] `DELETE /tasks/1` removes the task\n- [ ] Frontend shows three columns: \"To Do\", \"In Progress\", \"Done\"\n- [ ] Adding a task makes it appear in \"To Do\"\n- [ ] Changing the dropdown moves the task to the correct column\n- [ ] Deleting a task removes it from the view\n- [ ] Page refresh preserves data (it's in PostgreSQL)\n\n## Distribution Plan\n\nLocal only. No distribution. Run with `node server.js`, open `index.html` in browser.\n\n## Next Steps\n\n1. Create the PostgreSQL database and `tasks` table\n2. Initialize the Node.js project (`npm init -y && npm install express pg`)\n3. Write `server.js` with the pg connection and 4 CRUD endpoints\n4. Write `index.html` with the 3-column layout, task cards, and fetch-based CRUD\n5. Test: add a task, move it through columns, delete it, refresh to verify persistence\n\n## The Assignment\n\nOpen `psql` and run the CREATE TABLE command yourself — type it out, don't copy-paste. You'll learn more from the typos and error messages than from getting it right the first time.\n\n## What I noticed about how you think\n\n- You had the FlowBoard spec two days ago — a full production Kanban with 10+ models, real-time sync, auth, drag-and-drop. Now you're here with one table and four endpoints. That's not giving up — that's knowing that learning fundamentals first makes the complex version actually buildable. That instinct separates people who build things from people who design things.\n- Your \"strictly exclude\" list was longer than your feature list. No auth, no validation, no error handling, no Docker, no testing, no CORS config, no drag-and-drop, no animations, no comments. That takes discipline. Most people can't resist adding \"just one more thing.\" You can.\n","numLines":182,"startLine":1,"totalLines":182}}}
